@mcatanzaro pinentry isn't build dependency of gnupg. You don't have to rebuild gnupg if you add pinentry in g-b-m. Moreover gcr IS dependency of pinentry if you want to build gnome3 backend (which is what most gtk apps would be interested to use). As gnome specific tool gcr is available in g-b-m but not in fdo. It's also build against g-b-m glib/gtk specific versions which means even if fdo added them you won't be able to inherit those directly but would have to rebuild them yourself. Similar problem would be with building libsecret support.

The same things goes for qt backend which could be only being build in kde platform thus shipping backend-less pinentry in fdo would be pointless.

Considering above I think this is g-b-m decision if they want to include pinentry in Platform.

@Icx4Orange Did you set the graphics driver to performance mode? (Nvidia X Server Settings > PowerMizer > Preferred Mode > Prefer Maximum Performance)

I had the same issue with all recent Gnome versions, because the GPU would run at low clock speed, not being able to provide stable 60 FPS, because it would permanently switch between clock speeds while dragging. If an application does utilize the GPU, the clock speed would be kept high. Resulting in fluid window movement.

My System: Ubuntu 18.04, 18.10, 19.04, 19.10 (and respective Gnome Shell versions) on Nvidia GTX 1070 Ti.
